I am humbled and honored to be able to serve the hardworking people of Florida’s Second Congressional District and represent their conservative values in Congress. I’m looking forward to hitting to the ground running and getting some real work done. It’s not going to be easy, but we will fix our broken health care system, strengthen our military and the economy, provide for our veterans, and protect the Second Amendment.
Behind the scenes look at yesterday's swearing in ceremony! #OpeningDay
Make sure to follow me on Twitter at @DrNealDunnFL2!

Last night, I proudly cast my first votes as a member of the 115th Congress on two bills that will work to improve the lives of our veterans and ensure accountability at the VA. Veterans across our nation fought for our freedom, they shouldn’t have to fight here at home to get the care they need and deserve. As an Army veteran myself, please know that I will fight for our veterans in Congress!  http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/house-votes-to-end-va-scrubbing-of-employee-records/article/2610806

Today, I voted to rein in President Obama’s overregulation and to stop him from implementing harmful regulations just days before the end of his presidency. Overregulation under the Obama Administration has crippled our economy and left small businesses and hardworking Florida families struggling to stay afloat. The American people undoubtedly wanted a change by electing Donald Trump as our next President, sending a clear message that the overreach and burdensome regulations by President Obama needs to be stopped.  http://dunn.house.gov/media/press-releases/dr-dunn-votes-rein-obama-during-final-days-presidency
Proud to have voted for the Midnight Rules Relief Act!  http://fosterfollynews.com/2017/01/05/dr-dunn-votes-to-rein-in-obama-during-finals-days-of-presidency/

Today, I took part in the reading aloud of the U.S. Constitution on the floor of the House of Representatives by reciting Article I, Section 7, Clause 2, more commonly known as the “pocket veto clause.” The reading of the Constitution aloud is a statement to the American people that we, as a Congress, are dedicated to upholding the sacred, fundamental values put forth by our forefathers.

Yesterday, the House voted to condemn the anti-Israel United Nations Security Council Resolution which was passed last month. President Obama’s decision to abstain from the vote, instead of vetoing it, is a betrayal of our relationship with Israel. I will continue to support Israel, our ally, and the one beacon of freedom and democracy in the Middle East. In 14 days Donald Trump will be inaugurated as President, and Israel will have no doubt that the United States has its back.  https://foreignaffairs.house.gov/blog/standing-ally-israel

Today, a Joint Session of Congress certified the Electoral College ballots and officially recognized Donald Trump as the next President of the United States. It is an honor to take part in confirming Donald Trump as our next President. The American people spoke loud and clear about the need for change in Washington in November. I look forward to working with President-Elect Trump and Vice President-Elect Pence to tackle the tough issues that are plaguing this nation. Now it’s time to roll up our sleeves and truly make America great again.  https://dunn.house.gov/media/press-releases/dr-neal-dunn-s-statement-congress-certifying-donald-trump-president-elect

Do you know a current college or graduate student, or a recent graduate who is interested in politics and government? All three of my offices (Panama City, Tallahassee, and Washington, DC) are looking for interns who are ready to work hard, while learning about the legislative process. Applicants should be well-organized, responsible, reliable, enthusiastic, as well as possess excellent communication skills. Candidates must be willing to work in a fast-paced environment. No previous Hill experience is necessary. All interested applicants should email their cover letter and resume to  fl02interns@gmail.com.
Get ready for some good news out of Washington for once!

The House Committee on Veterans' Affairs, House Agriculture Committee, and House Committee on Science, Space, and Technology are fundamental to Florida’s future, to our economy and to the welfare of our veterans. I’m honored to serve and be a strong, conservative voice for the Second District on these committees.   http://dunn.house.gov/media/press-releases/dr-neal-dunn-appointed-three-key-house-committees

As a small business owner, and having traveled throughout the Second Congressional District, one of the biggest issues our job creators are running into is overregulation. In the past 8 years, the Obama Administration has implemented more than 600 new regulations, having over $740 billion in economic effects. To put this into perspective, on average, President Obama implemented a new harmful regulation every three days during his eight years in office. The Regulatory Accountability Act of 2017 will work to help solve the problem of government overreach, and cut down on burdensome regulations and government-knows-best policies.
Tonight at 7:05 PM ET I will be hosting a live telephone town hall! Click the link below to listen in and ask questions!  http://apps.facebook.com/videoteleforum/streaming.php?client=16350

Today we took the first step in repealing and replacing Obamacare by passing the budget resolution. Obamacare is failing. Lost coverage, skyrocketing premiums, unaffordable deductibles, crushing costs for small businesses. As a doctor I’ve seen it all first-hand. We need to fix this broken system and create one that works for all Americans, including those with pre-existing health conditions. We will ensure there is a smooth transition with no gaps in coverage.  http://dunn.house.gov/media/press-releases/dr-neal-dunn-votes-expedite-obamacare-repeal-and-replace

We had a great telephone town hall this week, thank you to all who listened in and asked questions. If you ever have a question or opinion about the work I am doing in Congress, or you need help with a federal agency, please reach out to my office at 202-225-5235 or at www.dunn.house.gov. Looking forward to holding several more telephone town halls this year and hearing directly from you!

Leah and I were saddened to hear of the passing of a close family friend and astronaut, Gene Cernan, the last man to stand on the moon and Commander of Apollo 17. Gene was a true American hero, emblematic of the courage and fearlessness that propelled us into space. He spent his entire life serving this nation and his easy smile, kind words, and generous spirit will be greatly missed. He will always live on in the hearts of those who knew him and all who love this great nation.

Today we remember the seven lives lost 31 years ago on the Space Shuttle Challenger 7. The heroism of Michael J. Smith, Dick Scobee, Ronald McNair, Ellison Onizuka, Christa McAuliffe, Gregory Jarvis and Judith Resnik will not be forgotten.   President Reagan said it best, "We’ve grown used to the idea of space, and perhaps we forget that we’ve only just begun. We’re still pioneers. They, the members of the Challenger crew, were pioneers."  As we honor the crew of Challenger 7 today, let us remember that their spirit is still very much alive in America today. We still have among us those who possess the dreams, the faith, the courage and the tenacity to be pioneers in space and many other fields of endeavor. Let us all rededicate this day to honor not only the Challenger 7 Crew, but the pioneering spirit of America.  http://spacecoastdaily.com/2017/01/video-today-marks-31st-anniversary-of-space-shuttle-challenger-disaster-at-ksc/

It's common sense to set a temporary pause on immigration from countries that are bases of Islamic terrorism and recruitment. These countries were identified by the Obama Administration because of their links to terrorist recruitment activities, not any faith. Travelers with valid visas or green cards, including brave Iraqi translators who served our armed forces, should be allowed in with extreme vetting, and I'm glad the Administration is taking steps to clarify this policy. But let's be clear that the threat is real, and the terrorists want to use our immigration and refugee laws as a Trojan horse to come here and kill Americans. This measure is a first step in strengthening our vetting system so the terrorists from these nations cannot use our laws against us.  http://dunn.house.gov/media/press-releases/dr-neal-dunn-s-statement-president-trump-s-immigration-executive-order

The one-size-fits-all approach to federal regulations is devastating to America’s small businesses and workers. House Republicans are working hard to cut down on burdensome regulations and government-knows-best policies. Earlier this month we passed the Regulatory Accountability Act and the Regulations from the Executive in Need of Scrutiny Act, which will help stop overreaching regulations and bring transparency and accountability to the system.  https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=e5g2Wlg7yG0&feature=youtu.be

Another promise kept: President Trump just took the first step to dismantle the Waters of the U.S. regulation, a prime example of the Obama Administration’s bureaucratic overreach. This rule gave the EPA vast, new jurisdiction over private property -- land that may include culverts, ditches, and shallow ponds that flood in a heavy rain. It’s nonsense, and we can’t get rid of this Washington power grab soon enough.

Tonight, we heard the President outline his optimistic plan for the country, which included tackling the tough issues of tax and regulatory reform, fixing our broken health care system, rebuilding our military, and keeping our commitment to our veterans. The VA only covers transplants performed at a Veterans Affairs Transplant Centers, and waiting times for a transplant at the VA centers are on average 32 percent longer than those at non-VA facilities. The VICTOR Act will change that – allowing veterans to seek care at a local, federally certified organ transplant facility. Our veterans and wounded warriors have earned this care through their service and sacrifice, and as they did not let us down, we cannot let them down.   https://dunn.house.gov/media/press-releases/dr-dunn-champions-crucial-veterans-legislation

The Paris agreement breaks faith with the Americans we were elected to represent. The pact demanded that America meet stricter emissions standards than it did for China, Russia or India. It also compelled American taxpayers to fork over billions of dollars to other countries in a wealth redistribution scheme.‎ With rising energy prices, American workers would be forced to compete against foreign countries with one hand tied behind their backs, and it would cost our economy $2.5 trillion and 400,000 jobs by 2035. President Trump is right to walk away from a bad deal and put America first.

On June 6, 1944, more than 160,000 Allied troops landed at Normandy, France.  Despite brutal defenses they scaled those bluffs and secured a beachhead on the continent in the name of freedom and liberty. Today we honor the 73rd anniversary of D-Day, the beginning of the “Great Crusade,” which led to the Allied liberation of Western Europe from Nazi Germany. The courageous sacrifices of those troops lasted long past D-Day with 11 more months of hard-fought battles ending in Berlin and victory. We will never forget their sacrifices and their heroism which still inspires us today. Thank you to the Greatest Generation for giving us the greatest gift any mortal can give, freedom.

Today we recognize the founding principles of our great nation: the government is the servant of the people; the people are not the servants of the government. Government is just the tool we use to secure the inalienable rights God has given us. This was indeed a revolutionary concept for our Founding Fathers. From their time until the present, brave men and women have stood to defend those principles against tyranny, and many laid down their lives for them. We salute them. We celebrate the great country they have left for us, and take solemnly the obligation to pass it to our posterity. Freedom is safe with us. Happy Fourth to one and all.

Great breakdown of the Hearing Protection Act and the myths surrounding gun suppressors. I’ve been calling on the House to hold a vote on this important legislation since coming to Congress. Contrary to what is seen in the movies – suppressors do not silence gunfire. The typical decibel level of a handgun or rifle without a suppressor is enough to cause immediate and irreparable hearing damage. Suppressors can reduce the sound to that of a jackhammer.   https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/volokh-conspiracy/wp/2017/06/19/the-hearing-protection-act-and-silencers/?utm_term=.9fa85db8f7a5

DHS has some helpful tips to follow:  - Listen to local officials for updates and instructions. - Check-in with family and friends by texting or using social media. - Return home only when authorities indicate it is safe. - Watch out for debris and downed power lines. - Avoid flood water as it may be electrically charged. - Photograph the damage to your property in order to assist in filing an insurance claim. The Tax Cuts and Jobs Act will lower taxes on middle and lower income Americans.

The bill cuts taxes for the middle class. The 15% bracket is cut to 12%. The 25% bracket is cut to 22%. The standard deduction (claimed by 81% of residents in Florida’s Second District) is roughly doubled to $12,000 for individuals and $24,000 for married couples. The child tax credit is doubled to $2,000 per child ($1,400 of which is refundable, meaning you can benefit from it even if you have a negative tax liability and don’t owe the government any tax). A family of four making $55,000 will get a $1,500 tax cut. A single mother with one child making $30,000 will get an $800 check from the government.
Cutting taxes will give businesses of all sizes a boost, allowing many to expand and increase wages.

The bill replaces personal exemptions with a roughly doubled standard deduction, lower tax rates across-the-board, and a doubled child tax credit. This results in a lower overall tax bill. A family of five earning $65,000 will go from owing $735 to Uncle Sam under current law to getting a $1,460 check from the IRS because of the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act.  For instance:
Merry Christmas!

Low- and middle-income taxpayers receive the largest percentage cut in the bill. The group of taxpayers making between $40,000 and $50,000 per year will pay 56% less in taxes. Those making more than $1 million will pay 6% less. The bill puts more of the overall income tax burden on the wealthy, not less.
House Republicans have been working on cutting your taxes for years.
The Stafford family from Tallahassee made the trip up to DC to see all of the Christmas decorations. It was great having them stop by the office.

The bill changes U.S. corporate rates – which are currently the highest in the world – to match our trading competitors in Europe. This will make America a more competitive place to do business and create jobs. The bill cuts the rates for the same reason President Barack Obama wanted to in 2012: “Our current corporate tax system is outdated, unfair, and inefficient,” he said. “It provides tax breaks for moving jobs and profits overseas and hits companies that choose to stay in America with one of the highest tax rates in the world … That’s why my administration released a … framework that lowers the corporate tax rate and broadens the tax base in order to increase competitiveness for companies across the nation.”

The mortgage interest deduction stays exactly the same for current mortgages. For new mortgages, taxpayers may deduct interest incurred on principal up to $750,000. Taxpayers can still deduct interest incurred new mortgages with principal over $750,000, but only interest payments associated with the first $750,000. This system is in place now, but the deductibility cap is $1 million.

The Tax Cuts and Jobs Act preserves the medical expenses deduction and the deduction for classroom supplies. It also does not tax the value of graduate school tuition waivers. Current law does not change for any of these provisions in the tax code.

The Tax Cuts and Jobs Act repealed the Obamacare individual mandate. In its decision upholding the law, the U.S. Supreme Court ruled that the ACA’s individual mandate is a tax. In fact, it’s a tax that disproportionately falls on low- and middle-income taxpayers, as 85% of those who paid the penalty tax make less than $50,000 per year, according to the IRS.
